1. What is SPKRID ?
--------------------
    SPKRID is a text-dependent Speaker Identification System, developed as
an undergraduate project at the University of Mumbai. SPKRID is written
entirely in C++ (with a few C modules), most of which is ANSI compatible.
It is a highly modular and extensible system. As of now, SPKRID can run only
on the 32-bit Windows platform.


2. Obtaining SPKRID
--------------------
    SPKRID is distributed under the GNU General Public License (see the
accompanying file COPYING). SPKRID is available either in source form or
as pre-built binaries for the Win32 platform. In case you did not receive
the source code, you can download it free of charge from my home page
http://www.geocities.com/sankaraonline/


3. Building SPKRID
-------------------
    SPKRID is highly modular and ANSI compliant to a large extent, but the
user interface and audio components are system dependent. Thus, the system
compiles and runs correctly only on Win32 systems. It is a straightforward
exercise to replace the system dependent modules with those appropriate for
other platforms. The current source distribution compiles correctly with
any 32-bit Windows C++ compiler that supports all routines in CONIO.H. It
has been tested with Borland C++ 5.5 for Win32 (free command line tools).
You will also require a sound card, speakers and microphone along and the
appropriate Windows drivers installed (make sure it works in Windows). Make
sure that you have sufficient disk space (about 5 MB is sufficient for a
small system).

    A MAKEFILE is included with the distribution to automate the build
process. To build the source, follow these steps:

a) Unzip the archive to a folder, say C:\SPKRID. This creates a subdirectory
   called SRC within SPKRID, which contains the source and support files.

b) Make sure you have BCC32 5.5 installed and that it works properly (you
   can get BCC32 5.5 free from Borland's website: http://www.borland.com/).

c) Switch to the SRC folder. Here you will find a couple of C++ files, a
   folder called 'classes' and a 'makefile'. If you want to use a different
   compiler or change other options, edit the 'makefile'.

d) Type 'make' at the command prompt. This compiles SPKRID, and creates the
   desired path structure. Under default conditions, a folder 'BIN' is
   created under SPKRID; this contains the executable files.

e) Type 'cd..\bin' to switch to the 'BIN' folder. You can now run SPKRID.


4. Running SPKRID
------------------
    SPKRID consists of two independent modules:

a) ADMINCP: This is the Administrator Control Panel, from which profiles can
   be managed. Users can be added, removed, viewed, and profiles can be
   imported/exported from/to other databases.

b) USERAPP: This is the User Module, which performs the actual identification
   activity. Automatic identification or Manual Verification are possible.

   To run these modules, type 'admincp' or 'userapp' at the command prompt
in the 'BIN' folder. The modules are menu driven and easy to use.


